[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Today we\'re taking a look at what I consider to be the future workflow of AI filmmaking. And no, it is not nodes. Breathe a sigh of relief node haters. Rather, this is something that you\'ll be seeing quite a bit of in well different iterations over the next few months. And'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like all game changers, there will be good versions of it and there will be bad versions of it. So today at Baseline, I\'m going to go over how you can build a customized one for yourself, plus some tips and tricks I learned'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'along the way. Kicking off a few days ago, I released Paperclip, a short kind of Black Mirroresque film about the AI apocalypse that no one sees coming. Yes, your AI girlfriend is going to enslave humanity.'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you haven\'t caught the film yet, I I mean, I do recommend checking it out first. The link is down below. Uh mostly because we\'re going to talk about it in the context of this workflow. And you know, I mean, I\'m pretty proud of this'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one. So, do feel free to hop over and give it a watch or, you know, if you want to watch it after, although spoilers ahead. And to that, before we actually head into production, I did just briefly want to talk about pre-production and kind of the why of it'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all. As someone in the comments mentioned, no, this was not a weekend project. It it was definitely a longer stew for sure. Although, I do have to say production itself did go fairly quickly, but the idea itself has been'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'noodling around for quite a bit. Well, I mean to be honest, uh since Open AI suggested that they were going to release a spicy mode for Chad GPT voice, they did ultimately pull back on that particular side quest. But I would say'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that combined with the uh doomer galvanic sable scenario that was presented in if anyone builds it, everyone dies. Like both of those kind of got the old creative nog and hum. What followed was a lot of brainstorming'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and research kind of poking at it in the background over like the last couple of months. Uh, I utilize Claude, which in my opinion is the more creative writer for the story breaks and arcs and Gemini\'s deep research for the factf'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finding and logic. In fact, Deep Research actually came up with a like a 20page paper on the technological, economic, and societal ramifications, which actually becomes the basis for most of the news report sections in the'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'film. Now, I do want to note that the script itself wasn\'t written in, you know, traditional script format. There really wasn\'t a need to do it that way. uh instead it\'s kind of done in this like hybrid uh like prompt and dialogue uh version that actually well Claude and'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I came up with um that said I mean for a production document uh for my use this worked totally fine. So after our script was locked it was time to move into production to that I once again'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'revisited the AI film pipeline from Dragon Blue which was the last AI film that I did. So I\'m not going to go too deep into the woods on this. I I did cover this in our last production breakdown. Uh but you know, essentially'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is a folder that lives on my desktop that can plug into claude or chat GPT or basically anything that can parse an MD file, which is markdown file or kind of like the instructions for one'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of these LLM systems. If you\'re new to all of this, don\'t stress it. It actually is very easy. But I will say that I do recommend uh using Claude in either co-work or code mode. Uh basically anything that isn\'t chat. The'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reason for this is that once again, we want this project living on our desktop or somewhere on our hard drive. Uh just not in a folder called stuff. That is a deep cut callback to longtime viewers. Basically, yeah, you want it living'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'somewhere on your computer. So, well, it knows where your stuff is. What all of this is is a set of instructions for Claude to read. I mean, you\'re not supposed to read this. You can if you want to, but I mean, it\'s really meant for Claude. Um for it to become your production office. All you have to do is'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'open up a new session, point it at your folder, and ask it to review the quick start. And well, I mean, you\'re pretty much off and running. Now, what are you running? Well, again, I mean, it is pretty much your AIL production office.'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Um, so it\'ll do a story breakdown of anything that you throw into it, breaking things down into scenes. Um, you can go through a style guide with it where it\'ll lock in the style, uh, character reference grids for all of'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your characters that can be generated in Nano Banana Pro 2K or really whatever you want. Um, we\'ll go over that later on. Um, it\'ll do every all of your scenes as a 2x two grid um in Nano Banana Pro or once again image 2 if you'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to or really again anything else. Um, this particular one has uh seedance 2.0 prompts that I personally like to use. Again, you can swap them out, but the default there is the prompt format'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that I I like. Um, and then it also has a production brief and a full production tracker as well. So, um, yeah, I mean, it is again, it\'s kind of your home office. Now, is all of this useful? In'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'my opinion, yes, very much so. Uh, considering that the project itself knows what your film is about, knows what it looks like, knows who\'s in it. So, it really does speed up the creation'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'process a pretty considerable amount. Uh, the other big part of it is the asset tracking because I, well, I mean, frankly, I\'m I\'m always a mess with that. So, it\'s nice to have something that\'s keeping track of it. Is it perfect? No, it\'s not. We\'ll go over'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that stuff later on, but I I mean I\'ll point out that this is like the eighth iteration that I\'ve done on this mostly because again things keep changing. I do want to note that I\'ll have all of this available for you in this week\'s'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'newsletter. I\'ll just, you know, have the whole folder. You can download it. So, do make sure you\'re subscribed below. But the big change that\'s happened since the last time uh I built this was the introduction of MCPS. Now, MCPS are a big unlock. So big in fact'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that uh actually with this new skill uh the first time you load it up I actually had Claude ask like how do you want to run this? Do you want to run this with MCPS manually or some sort of hybrid format? Briefly if you\'re not familiar'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with what an MCP is beyond uh being the ultimate bad guy in Tron, the good Tron, the old old Tron. Uh an MCP is a model context protocol at at you know very baseline. It allows for your agent to,'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you know, have hands that reach into external programs and platforms to control them to that. Paper heart was generated via MCP over on martini. Who, yes, were kind enough to sponsor today\'s'

[06:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video. Now, one thing I do want to say is, and just be very upfront with you all, MCPs are popping up on a lot of platforms. So, I don\'t want to front and say like this is exclusive to Martini. That said, again, I I happen to like'

[06:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Martini, and there are a lot of other helpful features here as well, as we\'ll go over later on in the video. So, hooking up, in this case, a clawed MCP is kind of stupidly simple. Um, you just come up to your little uh gear icon'

[06:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. Um, make sure that MCP server here is turned on. Um, and then there are some like directions that are here. It\'s all fairly easy in terms of directions. I do recommend using claw desktop for'

[06:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this. Um but basically you know you just add a connector in desktop and then point it at this URL and you know pretty much you\'re you hit up you know always allow and off you go. Uh in cloud code there is a terminal command that you'

[07:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'throw in um very simple and then you know you essentially open up cloud code uh hit forward/mcp and you\'re off and running. Uh there\'s also it\'s also available on Gemini and on chat GPT as well though I haven\'t actually hooked'

[07:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'either of those two up. Once you\'ve done that, I mean, you\'re pretty much just directing your production office conversationally. Um, so I can say something like, um, create a 2x one uh image of Eli eating a hamburger in an'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In-N-Out. Uh, let\'s use Nano Banana. No, Nano Banana Pro in 2K. And there you go. Three images of our tech billionaire'

