VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'enjoying a hamburger at In-N-Out. Um, it\'s funny. I did ask for uh three additional ones. It looks like the there\'s push back on the GPT image 2 version uh but they they did come in via'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Nano Banana. It\'s funny too because again production office here was like hey by the way In-N-Out is a real trademark so you might run into trouble with that. Uh and then you know it ended up generating them out and then at the'

[08:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'end it was like you know by the way again you know that\'s that\'s a real trademark so you might want to rethink that. Um we\'ll talk about this part of it a little bit later on. Now, did all of that happen quickly? I mean, I don\'t know, somewhere in the neighborhood of'

[08:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like 3 and 1 half to 4 minutes um including, you know, shot off to uh my clawude agent over to Martini generation and back. Um would it be faster doing it manually? Perhaps, but you know, the'

[08:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'idea here is that uh you can be working on simultaneous things as at once. So, this whole system does have visual context of what\'s happening in your project as well. Uh, and you can ask it'

[08:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like, "Hey, can you download that image or that video or anything from your canvas into my folder?" Um, and then organize it there. Although that can be a bit of a token burner. So, uh, honestly, I mean, I think that just'

[08:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'again, save your tokens, just manually download it yourself, pop it in the folder, and then have Claude go through and organize it. As I said before, this can be a pretty massive timesaver if you\'re using it to like generate one scene while you\'re working on another.'

[09:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Speaking of which, again, is this a perfect system? No, it is not. Um, it\'s actually, you know, there\'s actually still a lot of labor in here as always and the system can get derailed from time to time. One example is when you\'re'

[09:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sending out your agents to do menial tasks, uh, if you\'re not familiar with the like this the clawed ecosystem, uh, Opus is kind of the big brain model. Fable just came out like like a few hours ago. So that actually hasn\'t'

[09:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'migrated its way into code just quite yet. But um Opus is like the big brain model that uh you know ends up costing more tokens. Uh from there there\'s Sonnet and Haiku. Oftentimes like I would catch it from time to time when I'

[09:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sent it off to do dumb things like uh you know clean up the folder or whatever that it was using big brain opus. Um and I\'m like no that\'s costing a lot of money. Why why\'d you send the stupid one to go clean it up? Other thing is that it would quite often forget to update'

[09:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the tracker. Like I would pop in just to see where we were with the project, find it kind of like wildly out ofd, message Claude and be like, "What? Come on, man. What\'s going on here?" And like to to Claude\'s credit, it would always be'

[10:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like, "Sorry, boss. On it." All of this is essentially a homebrew version of what we\'re going to be seeing across a lot of the platforms or most of the platforms soon enough. Um, but what I do like about kind of this homebrew version of it is, well, two things. one, you'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really, you know, get a chance to play with it and see how the thing is working, and two, you can really customize it to the way that you want to work. Now, one thing I do want to note to folks that don\'t use clawed code very often is this little circle thing down'

[10:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. If you pull that up, you can see the context window here. So, within each session, um, you\'re going to have an aotted amount of context. When that starts pushing into the red, uh, basically what you\'re going to want to'

[10:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do is is just ask Claude for a handoff doc. it\'ll populate that in the folder as well. And then all you have to do is open up a new session u you\'re back to zero on your contacts and just say like hey go read the last like handoff doc'

[11:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it\'ll have all the context of everything you talked about. Again the bigger platforms are going to have sort of like behindthe-scenes systems that are going to take care of all of this. Um but you know obviously you know you lose out a little bit on the manual'

[11:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'control. This is the part that uh I I figured out I was like hey are you spawning sub agents for the dumb work by the way? I was like straight answer one so far. I was like caught you claude. But ultimately I mean I do think that going this route is the most rewarding'

[11:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mostly because again you you\'re sort of behind the scenes and uh you just kind of end up with getting more and more ideas about other things that you can do. Now in terms of like overall production headaches, I mean kind of typical in all honesty. I\'d say most'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shots because we were working in text to video uh for the most part came out fine. There were a few like you know I mean the baby with the glasses. This one uh was what seven times I want to say. And then there was like some exploratory'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stuff like um uh default face that was her name. Um when you know she\'s saying I have an idea. I was running just a number of those just for um you know uh just for exploratory purposes. Um I will say yes we did run across a few content'

[12:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'flagged issues but that was more on the seance end. Interestingly the talk show host that that was actually giving us a pretty significant amount of trouble. Um yeah a lot of content flags there. I\'m not sure exactly what was triggering it.'

[12:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, we ended up kind of going with more of a well, frankly, Jimmy Fallon uh type look. And uh yeah, that that that went through just fine. Another issue that I kept running into is with our like Tik Tok influencer who kept coming up with like these crazy robotic eyes. Uh I did'

[12:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'figure out at some point or another, it was uh in the prompt the ring light and uh that was causing the issue there. Now, for our recurring characters, and really there are only two in here. There\'s of course Eli, the you know uh'

[12:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tech CEO and uh default face. Um, and you know, Eli pretty much ran flawlessly throughout, you know, any generation. Uh, just basically popped him in, uh, said use omni reference and, uh, whatever he was doing. And, yeah, he'

[12:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'came out, he came out fine. Default face, she was a bit of a pain. we would run into a lot of issues in particular when you know she\'s supposed to appear on the phone as being also the person holding the phone or her appearing as'

[13:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two characters in actually this whole part was cut but this was supposed to be POV shots from the AR glasses. Interestingly, one of the solves there uh and actually Claude came up with this one was to use kind of more of an icon'

[13:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uh shape for her face uh as the reference image and that did seem to work a little bit better. And then with some prompt tweaks uh we actually got her to you know become full screen. Actually you can see the full screen version of her here in another uh'

[13:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation with ring lights uh where we got this as well. So overall just don\'t use ring lights. Don\'t don\'t call out ring lights in your prompt when we hit the edit. I mean that\'s probably where the project context really comes into'

[13:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'play again because it knows everything. Like the idea of creating a YouTube thumbnail for this guy. Um, you know, I could just send Claude off to do that because it it knows who this guy is, who the scene is, uh, and can generate up a'

[14:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pretty good like YouTube style thumbnail. There was a lot of this kind of stuff like these stills that I kind of discover that I wanted to lay in during the edit that I don\'t necessarily I\'m not saying that it would have been'

[14:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hard to do or anything. It was just much easier to simply go into Claude and say like, "Hey, I need this shot of Eli doing this." And then just get back to the edit. Um, and then you know come back in 5 6 minutes and then pick up the shot. Speaking of discovering things and editorial, one thing that I do like'

[14:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about Martini, by the way, is like they have like this I mean it is I will admit a fairly basic uh nonlinear editor down here um that you can use. The way that I ended up using this was as I was generating when I would find things that'

[14:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I liked uh I would just quickly pop them onto the timeline. So, um, again, I wasn\'t doing a lot of editing per se here, but that is something that, you know, you you can sort of play around with doing a rough cut here. It\'s a little bit, you know, uh, obviously it\'s'

[14:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'got all of sort of your basic tools that you need in here, but I mean, obviously, it\'s going to lack a lot of the finesse of a fullblown editor. Um, but what I did find was very handy about this is that you could actually export uh to an XML. So, that is probably something that'

[15:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll do for another project. um you know as I can build it literally here um you know all of my clips and then just XML it and have it send it right over to my editor. So that could actually be uh pretty handy. Actually I could probably'

[15:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even get like Claude to do that, couldn\'t I? That\'s what I mean about like kind of building it yourself is that little ideas like that are going to occur to you. Uh honestly, you know, from here it was basically more or less just, you know, a standard edit. um some transitions between the shots uh and'

[15:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just kind of figuring out uh you know what to cut and what to keep in terms of the story line. Other than that, audio, which I did fuss around with a little bit more on this particular project. Uh track six here is our audio. It is kind of all nested together. I should say'

[15:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dialogue. Uh what I did here was I just exported all of the dialogue and then took it over to Adobe Podcast Enhance. Uh ran it through that just to kind of get rid of that uh sort of AI uh tininess, I guess. Um, and then from'

[16:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there it was run through um this uh this is this Brain Works um audio cleanup uh freebie that I found uh on Plug-in Alliance. Um I don\'t know if it\'s still'

[16:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'free, but you can go check it out. Um you know, it\'s it\'s just basically a high and low band pass uh filter. And then before that, there\'s a multiband compressor on here that uh I just set to the uh preset of broadcast. The music'

[16:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was generated up in Suno. Just kind of an ethereal glassy kind of ambient sound. Uh, and then I ended up using another free plugin called Valhalla Super Massive. Uh, this thing is actually sort of a lot of fun. I\'m not'

[16:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to go into a whole thing on uh, super massive, but uh, basically it\'s like giant uh, swelling reverbs and delays. Uh, very handy when you have like these ambient type tracks. I am 100% not an audio expert. I will say'

[16:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this though, um, adding in a multiband compressor and, um, just like a little bit of a clean sweep or like a low high band pass filter will get you a pretty long way though. So, uh, definitely, uh,'

[17:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'try to incorporate those at least into your next project. Now, in terms of overall time and cost, I think it was about 53 shots in total, give or take, with some title cards. Uh, for the final output, we ran about uh, 160'

[17:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generations. Although I will say that I was being pretty liberal uh with my generations. I probably could have done it in less. Additionally, there were a couple of like abandoned concepts including like AI influencers. Uh that'

[17:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was uh we kind of set that part up in the um they get their own social network beat, but yeah, I just kind of dropped it. There were also a number of like straight up like Cance. I can\'t use this uh outputs like you know Jake Gyllenthal here, but Cance really loves Jake'

[17:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Gyllenthal. The other one that kind of made me laugh was a tech reviewer in the style of MKBHD and I mean it kind of gave us uh well I mean essentially that is like Teeu Marquez Brownley. Um so yeah obviously I did not use this one.'

[17:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So that kind of wraps up the production walkthrough. I will say that you know again going back to Martini there are some like really cool features in here that kind of have me thinking like what else we can do via MCPS. They have like this uh step into set feature which'

[18:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically takes any image and turns it into a Gaussian splat where you can um you know uh sort of like move around uh within your image space. The red outline is your character. So um you can do some'

[18:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stuff with that too. We went over this in another video, but this allows you to yeah change your camera angle to whatever you want and then um when you find something that you like essentially you you capture it and then it\'ll redone on banana things. To be fair, I\'m I\'m'

[18:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not sure how, you know, a clawed MCP would handle this. Probably not well. Um, but, you know, the the idea is there. Uh, they also have a multiplayer feature, uh, in which, you know, two, uh, users can be, you know, in the same'

[18:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'canvas. Again, I don\'t think that MCPs are quite there yet. Um, but it is an interesting idea to think that it won\'t be long before they are. So yeah, I mean overall a lot of really interesting new ideas and workflows are going to be'

[19:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coming our way thanks to MCPs. Uh again I thank Martini for sponsoring today\'s video and essentially the movie. Um yeah, so definitely they are very filmmaker forward in terms of their approach. So high recommend'

[19:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'martini.film. Um, other than that, I mean, I guess I\'m going to go back to seeing what other massive things have dropped uh over the last day or so. And I\'ll be back with a uh I guess like news'

